<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD RACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE LILAC TIME"The Lilac Time." Mercury ** 1/2 
</P>
<P>
One-time British New Romantic pop-fop star Stephen Duffy's transformation, in 
these folkier days, into contemplative idyllist may strike some (at least the 
few in the United States who have heard of him) as a bit calculated. But this 
album is so fresh and understatedly from-the-heart that if it is a calculation, 
it's a good one all around. As on the Waterboys' "Fisherman's Blues," the 
balance between the contemplation (primarily on the state of the English 
mind-set and the state of love) and the idyllic sound (lotsa airy acoustic 
guitars and lilting hooks, but not at the expense of drive) is the key: Call it 
strum and Drang. Maybe the sound's not entirely new, but it's truly romantic. 
STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
