<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THE FORBIDDEN ZONE BY MICHAEL LESY (ANCHOR BOOKS / 
DOUBLEDAY: $7.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELENA BRUNET 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the advent of his father's mortal illness, Michael Lesy sets off to confront 
the subject of death, the "forbidden zone." 
</P>
<P>
"Our culture is permeated by images and accounts of death," Lesy writes, "but 
they are only fictions, the works of the imagination, counterfeits. The real 
thing is carefully hidden." 
</P>
<P>
Lesy travels across the United States interviewing pathologists, homicide 
detectives, undertakers, slaughterhouse workers as well as murderers, 
executioners and mercenaries, all of whom distance themselves from their work 
-- through humor, ritual, religion. 
</P>
<P>
Among the conversations Lesy relays, a Charleston undertaker tells him that 
Charles de Gaulle's protection against death by poisoning was to take a pinch 
of arsenic every day. "A little death every morning to live through the big 
one." From an AIDS physician, Lesy hears: "You die the way you live. There are 
very few last-minute transformations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA030589-0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 26652 </DOCID>
