<P>
Book Review; Page 14; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
181 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: A FRIEND FROM ENGLAND BY ANITA BROOKNER (HARPER &amp; ROW: 
$6.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELENA BRUNET 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirty-two-year-old Rachel Kennedy, owner of a London bookshop, is 
self-sufficient, solitary. "I've learned how to be alone and to put a good face 
on it," she says. 
</P>
<P>
She becomes a frequent dinner guest at the home of her father's former 
accountant and his wife, Oscar and Dorrie Livingstone. Somehow Rachel concludes 
"that Oscar and Dorrie thought me a suitable companion for Heather," their 
grown daughter, and Rachel condescends to become her mentor. 
</P>
<P>
When Heather impulsively flies to Venice to marry the man she loves, Rachel 
follows her -- to reprimand her. Heather responds by saying that Rachel's own 
total control -- good manners masking disengagement -- amounts to a 
"mismanagement" of life. 
</P>
<P>
In the end, Rachel admits her limitations: "To strike out and claim one's own 
life . . . even to embrace caprice, was, though monstrous, sometimes 
admirable." 
</P>
<P>
"What we are reading is . . . an allegorical fable between a false life of 
repression and a true life of risks and engagements," Hermione Lee wrote in 
these pages, calling "A Friend From England" a "harsh, dark fable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
