166 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: SUITE FOR CALLIOPE A NOVEL OF MUSIC AND THE CIRCUS BY ELLEN 
HUNNICUTT (LAUREL / DELL PUBLISHING: $7.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELENA BRUNET 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ada Cunningham (stage name Norma) finds refuge in the unlikely company of a 
lioness, an aging trapeze artist, a popcorn magnate and the remnants of a 
circus troupe near retirement. 
</P>
<P>
Her real family was no less eccentric than her current company. Her mother, 
Grace (who died when Ada was 8), was a newspaper columnist who fabricated some 
of her best stories, the most popular of which was about her prodigy daughter: 
Ada, she reported, could read and write both English and Latin by age 3 and 
play violin, piano and compose music. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, Ada is partly handicapped. 
</P>
<P>
Her father, Reynard, a violinist for the Indianapolis Symphony, is committed to 
a sanitarium by the time Ada is 16. But the early music training that he indeed 
gave her finds her a place in the circus: composing and playing music on the 
steam calliope. 
</P>
<P>
Ada's memories of her past, as well as the secret that caused her to flee 
Richmount, Ind., are interwoven into the narrative of circus life. An 
entertaining first novel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
