<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THOUSAND PIECES OF GOLD, A BIOGRAPHICAL NOVEL BY RUTHANNE 
LUM MCCUNN (BEACON PRESS, BOSTON: $8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELENA BRUNET 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ruthanne Lum McCunn has woven an enthralling work of fiction from the true life 
story of Lalu Nathoy (known later as Polly Bemis), a Chinese pioneer who 
settled the American Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
Lalu was her father's favorite, his qianjin, or "thousand pieces of gold." But, 
after his crop of winter wheat fails because of drought in 1871, he sells the 
teen-age Lalu to a band of raiding bandits for two sacks of soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
The bandit chief subsequently sells her to a brothel in Shanghai for 30,000 in 
taels. "Normally, I would not be able to buy a scrawny, dark-skinned girl with 
feet like dragon boats," the madam tells Lalu, "but today I have a special 
buyer who does not care about such things, someone who will take you to 
America." 
</P>
<P>
Traveling from San Francisco to Portland, Lalu is then brought by mule to the 
mining community of Warrens: Hong King, an aging Chinese saloon-keeper, has 
bought her to draw business, and renames her Polly. 
</P>
<P>
Later the white saloon-keeper next door, Charlie Bemis ("no one dares mess with 
him, he can keep a tin can dancing in the air with his six-shooter"), becomes 
her protector and eventually wins her from Hong King in a poker game -- and 
gives her her freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
