<P>
Anti-abortion demonstrators were hauled away by the busload from coordinated 
protests at women's medical clinics in three New England states. Arrests 
totaled more than 300, including two members of pro-choice groups that staged 
counter-rallies. Four busloads of demonstrators in Brookline, Mass., were 
booked on disorderly conduct charges. Other protests took place at abortion 
advocate Bill Baird's clinic in Boston; a Danbury, Conn., clinic, and at the 
Providence headquarters of Rhode Island Planned Parenthood. The simultaneous 
protests began at 7:45 a.m. at three Brookline clinics along a three-mile 
stretch of Beacon Street. "What we want to do is witness the life and so gum up 
the works (that) no longer is it possible to kill unborn children, so the legal 
system simply can't deal with the closing of the clinics. They can't arrest 
everybody," said Father David Mullen of St. Paul's Roman Catholic Church in 
Wellesley, a protest organizer. 
