<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS BRIEFS: WESTSIDE GROWTH SLOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By David M. Kinchen 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite all the new apartment buildings going up in Mar Vista, Palms and 
Brentwood the Westside has grown by only about 79,000 since the 1980 census, 
according to a new study by the Los Angeles County Department of Regional 
Planning. 
</P>
<P>
Every Westside community except Marina del Rey -- which dropped from 6,693 in 
1980 to 6,285 in 1988 -- gained population during the 8-year period. The 
Westside's population rose from 966,150 in 1980 to 1,045,425 last year. 
</P>
<P>
County analyst Terry Bills, a Mar Vista resident, was initially surprised by 
the figures, noting that three-story apartment buildings had replaced many of 
the single-family houses: "The data is right. It's simply that when we live 
close to construction, we tend to see it as more pervasive than it is." David 
M. Kinchen 
</P>
</TEXT>
