<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY LINES: NEW WAVES ON RODEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Leon Whiteson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Designer Ettore Sottsass, a founder of the Milan-based Memphis Group, 
internationally acclaimed for its New Wave architecture and furniture designs, 
has completed his first project in California, a striking new art gallery on 
Beverly Hills' Rodeo Drive. 
</P>
<P>
The most distinctive feature of the Mayer-Schwarz gallery is its frontage. A 
facade of black Marquina marble is punctured by a dramatic doorway made up of 
irregular folds and jagged angles of multicolored terrazzo. 
</P>
<P>
The doorway conveys a sense of mystery, as if giving entry to a hidden cave of 
art in the midst of Beverly Hill's opulent Golden Triangle shopping district -- 
a cave Sottsass decribes as "a metaphysical place." Leon Whiteson 
</P>
</TEXT>
