<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S., SOVIETS AGREE TO INCREASES IN THEIR EMBASSY STAFFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States and the Soviet Union have agreed to increases in their 
embassy staffs, reversing a cutback forced by the Reagan Administration after 
reporter Nicholas Daniloff was accused in Moscow of spying. 
</P>
<P>
Charles Redman, the State Department spokesman, said Friday that 18 positions 
were added last month to both the U.S. Embassy in the Soviet capital and to the 
Soviet Embassy here, along with two additional slots at the U.S. and Soviet 
consulates in Leningrad and San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
On Aug. 1, Redman said, 13 additional slots will be added to each of the 
embassies and two more to the consulates. The maximums then would be 256 for 
the embassies and 30 for the consulates. 
</P>
<P>
Daniloff's arrest -- he was subsequently released -- touched off a diplomatic 
tiff in which the Reagan Administration in October, 1986, imposed ceilings of 
225 at the embassies and 26 at the consulates. 
</P>
<P>
This forced the Soviets, which had a bigger staff, to withdraw about 80 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reversal, Redman said the workload at the U.S. Embassy and 
consulate had increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- EMBASSIES -- USSR; USSR -- EMBASSIES; UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN 
RELATIONS -- USSR; GOVERNMENT EMPLOYEES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
